{
  "doc_id": "45461",
  "text": "Our comprehensive database analysis of finished microbial genomes revealed at the time of the search (July 2013) the presence gene clusters. (B) Representatives of the organization of the ectoine/hydroxyectoine biosynthetic genes that deviate from the otherwise commonly found genetic organization. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0093809.g006 of ectoine biosynthetic genes [CITATION_1] in about 7% of the represented microorganisms, and about two thirds of these are predicted to produce hydroxyectoine [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] as well. Since hydroxyectoine often possess function-preserving and stress-relieving properties superior to those of ectoine [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , one wonders why not all ectoine producers synthesize 5-hydroxyectoine since this can readily be accomplished from ectoine in a single step [CITATION_10] . Part of the answer to this question becomes apparent when one considers the physiological requirements and the oxygen dependence of the ectoine/hydroxyectoine producer microorganisms. The EctDcatalyzed formation of 5-hydroxyectoine is an O 2 -dependent enzyme reaction [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] and consequently none of the predicted hydroxyectoine producers is an obligate anaerobe, whereas both aerobic and anaerobic microorganisms can produce ectoine (Fig. 1) .",
